Description

The format of an item within a collection describes its physical presence at the highest level.

History Note:

This vocabulary has been developed by referencing publicly available information from select libraries and archives about their FORMAT cataloguing terms.

National Film and Sound Archive's Formatscol

URI http://linked.data.gov.au/def/collection-item-format/national-film-and-sound-archive
Definition

The National Film and Sound Archive of Australia is Australia's audiovisual archive, responsible for developing, preserving, maintaining, promoting and providing access to a national collection of film, television, sound, radio, video games, new media, and related documents and artefacts.
Source https://www.nfsa.gov.au/
Members Tapecon, Diskcon, Digitalcon, Filmcon, Disccon, Documentationcon, Objectcon

State Library New South Wales' Formatscol

URI http://linked.data.gov.au/def/collection-item-format/state-library-new-south-wales
Definition

The State Library of NSW collects and preserves materials and evidence relating to our place in the world and makes them accessible to everyone in New South Wales and beyond.
Source https://www.sl.nsw.gov.au/
Members Object-SLNSWcon, Picturecon, Mapcon, Eresourcecon, Video & filmcon, Bookcon, Journal & magazinecon, Manuscriptcon, Newspapercon, Audiocon

Disccon

URI http://linked.data.gov.au/def/collection-item-format/disc
Definition

A sound recording on a thin, flat circular object, usually made of shellac, vinyl, or various laminates. The signal may be either analogue or digital, and recorded/played using acoustical, electrical, magnetic or optical technology.
Source https://www.iasa-web.org/cataloguing-rules/appendix-d-glossary

Diskcon

URI http://linked.data.gov.au/def/collection-item-format/disk
Definition

A round magnetic device for storing information and programmes accessible by computer; may be either a rigid platter (hard disk) or a sheet of flexible plastic (floppy disk or diskette). The disk base is coated with a magnetizable material on which data can be recorded or stored along concentric tracks as small magnetic areas forming patterns of binary digits or bits. Information is written onto the disk, and read from it in a disk drive, by read/write heads mounted on arms which move rapidly across the disk.
Source https://www.iasa-web.org/cataloguing-rules/appendix-d-glossary
Broader Concepts Digitalcon

Digital Versatile Disccon

URI http://linked.data.gov.au/def/collection-item-format/dvd
Definition

A round plastic, partly metal-coated disc used to store digital data which can be written and read by laser.
Source https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DVD

Filmcon

URI http://linked.data.gov.au/def/collection-item-format/film
Definition

A series of still images collected onto a flexible and transparent piece of film so that they can be projected in a rapid sequence so as to give the illusion of motion.
Source https://www.iasa-web.org/cataloguing-rules/appendix-d-glossary
Broader Concepts Video & filmcon

Broader Concepts Documentationcon

Mapcon

URI http://linked.data.gov.au/def/collection-item-format/map
Definition

A drawing of the earth's surface, or part of that surface, showing the shape and position of different countries, political borders, natural features such as rivers and mountains, and artificial features such as roads and buildings.
Source https://dictionary.cambridge.org/dictionary/english/map
Broader Concepts Documentationcon

Newspapercon

URI http://linked.data.gov.au/def/collection-item-format/newspaper
Definition

A regularly printed document consisting of large sheets of paper that are folded together, or a website, containing news reports, articles, photographs, and advertisements.
Source https://dictionary.cambridge.org/dictionary/english/newspaper
Broader Concepts Documentationcon

Objectcon

URI http://linked.data.gov.au/def/collection-item-format/object
Definition

A thing that you can see or touch but that is not usually a living animal, plant, or person.
Source https://dictionary.cambridge.org/dictionary/english/object
